  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "B — \"virtue\" in Laozi quote, then switch to \"character\" for author's analysis",
    "content": "**B. Use \"virtue\" in the Laozi block quote, then switch to \"(constitutive) character\" when the author begins their analysis.**\n\nThis is the right solution because the passage itself enacts a transition from classical text to the author's reinterpretation -- and the translation should make that transition visible.\n\nThe Laozi line is a *quotation*. It belongs to Laozi, not to the author. Translating it with standard renderings (\"virtue,\" \"benevolence,\" \"righteousness,\" \"propriety\") respects the source and gives the English reader the same recognition a Chinese reader has: \"ah, this is the famous passage from Chapter 38.\" If we render it as \"(constitutive) character\" from the start, we erase the reader's ability to recognize the quotation and compare it with translations they may already know.\n\nThen when the author begins their analysis -- introducing 现象礼, 现象仁, 现象义, and redefining 德 as \"that which makes a thing what it is\" -- the shift from \"virtue\" to \"character\" *performs* the author's philosophical move. The reader sees the standard term replaced by a new one and understands: the author is not using 德 the way Laozi meant it. The terminological shift enacts the conceptual shift.\n\nThe TN at the transition point writes itself: \"The author now departs from the standard reading of 德 as 'virtue.' In the analysis that follows, 德 is understood as (constitutive) character: the defining characteristics that make a thing what it is, assembled bottom-up from phenomena. See Glossary.\"\n\nThis also dissolves the entire debate we have been having. \"Virtue\" was never wrong for the Laozi quotation -- it was wrong for the *author's usage*. Option B lets each term serve the context it belongs to."
  }
}
